            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-10-11T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-10-11T06:00:00-05:00" n="381" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d381">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.C115 Paris/10–1145: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-10-11T12:00:00+01:00">October 11, 1945—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received October 11—10:40
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5971. For Wiesman<note n="21" xml:id="d381fn1">
                        <persName>Bernard Wiesman</persName>, Chief, International Labor
                        Organizations Branch, Division of International Labor, Social and Health
                        Affairs.</note> from <persName corresp="#p_MOE1">Mulliken</persName>.
                    Conversation with British Government ILO (International Labor Office)
                    representative reveals that British favored extending ILO invitation to Bulgaria
                    and Hungary and hence are not likely to oppose presence of representatives.
                    British oppose constitutional action by ILO except that absolutely necessary.
                    Canada taking same constitutional position. [<persName corresp="#p_MOE1">Mulliken</persName>.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
